      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I understand the constraints. A Fenwick Tree (also known as a Binary Indexed Tree) could be used for range sum queries, but given the large size of the grid and the number of queries, a standard Fenwick Tree might not be efficient or feasible due to memory limitations. Instead, you can use a Segment Tree with a more memory-efficient representation.\n\nHere's an example solution using a Segment Tree with a custom sparse representation:\n\n```python\nclass SegmentTree:\n    def __init__(self, size):\n        self.size = size\n        self.tree = [0] * (4 * size)\n        self.lazy = [0] * (4 * size)\n\n    def update_range(self, l, r, val):\n        self._update_range(0, 0, self.size - 1, l, r, val)\n\n    def _update_range(self, node, start, end, l, r, val):\n        if r < start or end < l:\n            return\n        if l <= start and end <= r:\n            self.tree[node] += val * (end - start + 1)\n            self.lazy[node] += val\n            return\n        mid = (start + end) // 2",
